as the day the Financial Times reported ( https://www.ft.com/content/1e677a=
7e-9494-4f5b-a724-9e58ef26b34f ) that Apple was about to be fined =E2=82=AC=
500 million. I felt comfortable writing about the fine based on that report=
 because, in my experience, European Commission decisions (1) Always break =
in the Financial Times, (2) the Financial Times report is followed by the o=
fficial press release a day or two later, and (3) the Financial Times repor=
t is invariably correct and the European Commission press release is invari=
ably vague and generally unhelpful.

In this case only the first and last assumptions held: the Financial Times =
did break this news, and the press release is vague and unhelpful ( https:/=
/ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_24_1161 ). However, the E=
uropean Commission took two weeks to issue that press release, and in the m=
eantime the fine increased by =E2=82=AC1.34 billion. I=E2=80=99m not entire=
ly sure what to make of this: was the initial leak some sort of trial ballo=
on, and there was substantial pushback about the fine being too low? Who ca=
n say!

Meanwhile, the press release doesn=E2=80=99t even mention Apple Music, whic=
h, as I noted in that Update, made this particular case a good one (i.e. it=
=E2=80=99s particularly unfair for Apple to use App Store rules to give App=
le Music an advantage); instead the decision simply says that =E2=80=9CAppl=
e=E2=80=99s anti-steering provisions amount to unfair trading conditions=E2=
=80=9D.

Here=E2=80=99s the thing, though: as far as I can tell, this ruling does no=
t apply to the App Store generally; rather, it only applies to =E2=80=9Cthe=
 market for the distribution of music streaming apps to iPhone and iPad use=
rs (=E2=80=98iOS users=E2=80=99) through its App Store.=E2=80=9D That, by e=
xtension, suggests that the order to remove the anti-steering provision onl=
y applies to music streaming apps?

As I=E2=80=99ve noted previously, I think that Apple=E2=80=99s anti-steerin=
g provision is the worst part of their App Store rules, and I think it=E2=
=80=99s blatantly anti-competitive in markets where Apple has its own alter=
native service (Apple Music, iBooks, Apple Fitness, etc.). At the same time=
, it=E2=80=99s really hard to not throw up your hands at the European Commi=
ssion=E2=80=99s approach here: there is no publicly available case law, the=
 market definition is hilariously narrow, and fines appear to be determined=
 by holding up a wet finger and seeing how the wind is blowing!

Apple=E2=80=99s Spotify Press Release
-----------------------------

With that in mind, you can understand part of the reason why Apple was peev=
ed about this result. The company issued a scathing press release ( https:/=
/www.apple.com/newsroom/2024/03/the-app-store-spotify-and-europes-thriving-=
digital-music-market/ ) that, at least in the first paragraph, criticized t=
he decision:

Today, the European Commission announced a decision claiming the App Store =
has been a barrier to competition in the digital music market. The decision=
 was reached despite the Commission=E2=80=99s failure to uncover any credib=
le evidence of consumer harm, and ignores the realities of a market that is=
 thriving, competitive, and growing fast.

The rest of the press release, though, isn=E2=80=99t about the European Com=
mission at all: instead it is almost completely directed at Spotify, and I =
don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99m overstating it to say that Apple=E2=80=99s =
venom and disdain is nearly tangible. Some snippets (but, by all means, rea=
d the whole thing ( https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2024/03/the-app-store-sp=
otify-and-europes-thriving-digital-music-market/ ) to see if I=E2=80=99m ov=
erstating things):

The primary advocate for this decision =E2=80=94 and the biggest beneficiar=
y =E2=80=94 is Spotify, a company based in Stockholm, Sweden. Spotify has t=
he largest music streaming app in the world, and has met with the European =
Commission more than 65 times during this investigation. Today, Spotify has=
 a 56 percent share of Europe=E2=80=99s music streaming market =E2=80=94 mo=
re than double their closest competitor=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94 and pays Apple =
nothing for the services that have helped make them one of the most recogni=
zable brands in the world. A large part of their success is due to the App =
Store, along with all the tools and technology that Spotify uses to build, =
update, and share their app with Apple users around the world=E2=80=A6

The theme of Spotify paying nothing comes up again and again in the press r=
elease; in fact, there is an entire section entitled =E2=80=9CSpotify Pays =
Apple Nothing.=E2=80=9D

Despite that success, and the App Store=E2=80=99s role in making it possibl=
e, Spotify pays Apple nothing. That=E2=80=99s because Spotify =E2=80=94 lik=
e many developers on the App Store =E2=80=94 made a choice. Instead of sell=
ing subscriptions in their app, they sell them on their website. And Apple =
doesn=E2=80=99t collect a commission on those purchases=E2=80=A6

It takes continuous effort and a lot of investment for Apple to make the to=
ols, the technology, and the marketplace that Spotify uses every day. We=E2=
=80=99ve even flown our engineers to Stockholm to help Spotify=E2=80=99s te=
ams in person. And the result is that when a user opens the Spotify app, li=
stens to music on their commute, or asks Siri to play a song from their lib=
rary, everything just works. And again =E2=80=94 Spotify pays Apple nothing=
.

When it comes to doing business, not everyone=E2=80=99s going to agree on t=
he best deal. But it sure is hard to beat free.

When the Apple-Epic case went to trial, a lot of developers were upset abou=
t Apple=E2=80=99s contention that they deserved to be compensated for their=
 intellectual property; the truth, though, is that that was and remains a v=
ery strong legal argument. Still, I could see how it rubbed people the wron=
g way. After the trial concluded I wrote in App Store Arguments ( https://s=
tratechery.com/2021/app-store-arguments/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiI=
sImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiO=
iJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQ=
V00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIxL2FwcC1zdG9=
