This gets at the part of this case that is, to be perfectly honest, kind of=
 infuriating. Back in 2009 Apple came up with a memorable campaign for the =
iPhone:

( https://videopress.com/embed/6KC7wa7v?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

I admit it =E2=80=94 the first tweet above was wrong. Apple absolutely did =
a tremendous amount for developers. It invented the iPhone, it brought the =
concept of an App Store to the mass market, and it has iterated on both. An=
d yes, it spends a lot of money on APIs and developer tools.

What the company no longer admits, though, is that developers did a lot for=
 Apple too. They made the iPhone far more powerful and useful than Apple ev=
er would have on its own, they pushed the limits on performance so that cus=
tomers had reasons to upgrade, and even when Android came along iPhone deve=
lopers never abandoned the platform. Sure, they had good economic reasons f=
or their actions, but that=E2=80=99s the point: Apple had good economic rea=
sons for building out all of those APIs and developer tools as well.

What is so striking about this press release is how Apple=E2=80=99s legal a=
rgument has become its moral argument. This isn=E2=80=99t a somewhat sheepi=
sh Tim Cook on the stand making the case that Apple has the right to moneti=
ze its IP; this is Apple shouting from the rooftops that Spotify is some so=
rt of ungrateful malcontent who is taking advantage of Apple.

The next section is entitled =E2=80=9CSpotify Wants More=E2=80=9D:

But free isn=E2=80=99t enough for Spotify. They also want to rewrite the ru=
les of the App Store =E2=80=94 in a way that advantages them even more.

Like many companies, Spotify uses emails, social media, text messages, web =
ads, and many other ways to reach potential customers. Under the App Store=
=E2=80=99s reader rule, Spotify can also include a link in their app to a w=
ebpage where users can create or manage an account.

We introduced the reader rule years ago in response to feedback from develo=
pers like Spotify. And a lot of reader apps use that option to link users t=
o a webpage =E2=80=94 from e-readers to video streaming services. Spotify c=
ould too =E2=80=94 but they=E2=80=99ve chosen not to.

Instead, Spotify wants to bend the rules in their favor by embedding subscr=
iption prices in their app without using the App Store=E2=80=99s In-App Pur=
chase system. They want to use Apple=E2=80=99s tools and technologies, dist=
ribute on the App Store, and benefit from the trust we=E2=80=99ve built wit=
h users =E2=80=94 and to pay Apple nothing for it.

In short, Spotify wants more.

To be clear:

* The reader rule Apple was referring to was released 1 year, 11 months, an=
d 24 days ago ( https://www.theverge.com/2022/3/30/23003503/apple-reader-ap=
p-developer-external-link-guidelines-announced-entitlements ) ; =E2=80=9Cye=
ars ago=E2=80=9D is stretching it.
* The reader rule was introduced after a settlement with Japan=E2=80=99s Fa=
ir Trade Commission ( https://stratechery.com/2021/apples-app-store-concess=
ion-why-this-is-a-big-deal-devil-in-the-details/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJ=
SUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.e=
yJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1Ay=
WURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIxL2F=
wcGxlcy1hcHAtc3RvcmUtY29uY2Vzc2lvbi13aHktdGhpcy1pcy1hLWJpZy1kZWFsLWRldmlsLW=
luLXRoZS1kZXRhaWxzLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzEyMzk5MDE3LCJpYXQiOjE3MDk4MDcwMTcsImlzc=
yI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFk=
